Solution (Step-by-Step)
üîπ 1. Reload Docker's iptables NAT rules
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo systemctl restart docker
üîπ 2. Verify docker created the DOCKER chain
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo iptables -t nat -nL | grep DOCKER
You should see something like:

java
Copy
Edit
Chain DOCKER (2 references)
If not, continue below ‚¨áÔ∏è

üîπ 3. Ensure iptables-nft or iptables-legacy is installed
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo dnf install -y iptables iptables-nft
Then restart Docker again:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo systemctl restart docker
üîπ 4. Try running the registry again
bash
Copy
Edit
docker rm -f secure-registry

docker run -d \
  --restart=always \
  --name secure-registry \
  -v /opt/registry/data:/var/lib/registry \
  -v /opt/registry/auth:/auth \
  -v /opt/registry/certs:/certs \
  -e REGISTRY_HTTP_ADDR=0.0.0.0:5000 \
  -e REGISTRY_HTTP_TLS_CERTIFICATE=/certs/domain.crt \
  -e REGISTRY_HTTP_TLS_KEY=/certs/domain.key \
  -e REGISTRY_AUTH=htpasswd \
  -e REGISTRY_AUTH_HTPASSWD_REALM="Cloudera Docker Registry" \
  -e REGISTRY_AUTH_HTPASSWD_PATH=/auth/htpasswd \
  -p 5000:5000 \
  registry:2
